If the lock file is being created inside the `node_modules/node-locksmith` directory, this is likely happening because the module is using a relative path based on the file where the `LockManager` class is located (which is inside the `node_modules/node-locksmith` folder). This is not the desired behavior, as you would typically want the lock file to be created in the directory of the consuming application.

To address this, you should change the default value of the `lockFileDir` option from `__dirname` to `process.cwd()`. The `__dirname` variable gives you the directory of the file in which it is used (in this case, the directory of your module), whereas `process.cwd()` provides the current working directory of the Node.js process, which is the directory from where the application is run.

Here’s how you should modify the default options in your `LockManager` constructor:

```javascript
class LockManager {
  constructor(options = {}) {
    const defaults = {
      lockFileName: 'app.lock',
      lockFileDir: process.cwd(), // Use the current working directory
      killTimeout: 5000,
      waitForExitTimeout: 10000,
      checkInterval: 500,
      maxRetries: 3,
      defaultAnswer: 'yes'
    };
    // ... (rest of the constructor)
  }

  // ... (rest of the class methods)
}
```

This adjustment will set the default lock file location to the root directory of the consumer's Node.js project, which is where the consumer would expect the lock file to be created and found.

Make sure to update your module’s documentation as well to reflect this change, and inform users that they can customize the lock file location if they wish.

Also, as a best practice, make it clear in your module's API documentation that `lockFileDir` will default to the current working directory but can be customized according to user preference, so consumers of your module are aware of how to control the lock file location.
